This paper is about analyzing the performance of neural sequence-to-sequence models in machine translation. The paper discusses issues related to the uncertainty of the task and noisy training data, which are common topics in natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) research. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language), which covers NLP and ML topics. The paper also proposes tools to assess model calibration, which is related to model performance and optimization, suggesting that cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of search strategies and the spread of probability mass, which are related to optimization and algorithmic aspects of the models, suggesting that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of multiple human reference translations and the potential impact of noisy training data on model performance, which are related to data and evaluation aspects of the models, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also possible sub-categories.
